:::summary
Eastern philosophy encompasses the rich and diverse philosophical traditions of Asia — the Hindu philosophies of India, the Buddhist traditions originating in India and flowering across Asia, the Confucian and Taoist schools of China, and the meditative and martial traditions of Japan and Korea. These traditions address the same fundamental questions about reality, knowledge, the self, and the good life as Western philosophy, but often from strikingly different starting points, using different methods, and reaching different conclusions. A classically educated mind benefits enormously from engaging Eastern philosophy — not to abandon the Western tradition but to see it more clearly by comparison.
